Name: Dow Jones Spot Average
Metadata: The DJ Futures Price Index was introduced on October 3, 1933 and remained the same until July 5, 1950 when the index was broadened and a spot index was introduced.  The new index consisted of wheat, corn, oats, rye, wool tops, cotton, cottonseed oil, coffee, sugar, cocoa, rubber and hides. Additional revisions came in April of 1974, 1980 and 1982. The index is computed as a equal-weighted average of relative price indexes with a base of December 31, 1974 = 100, the day gold trading resumed in the United States. Prior to 1982, the base was 1924/1926= 100. The index includes grain and oilseed (corn, soybeans, and wheat), food and fiber (coffee, cotton, #2, sugar #11 world), Metals (copper, gold, silver), livestock and meat (live cattle and hogs), and wood (lumber).   Prior to January 1982, the Dow Jones Spot Price Index was based entirely on agricultural commodities, but it was revised in 1982 to include wood, livestock and meats, and metals.  The old Spot Index data can be converted to the old base by multiplying the data by 2.867.
